# No Scope Creep

## Never Implement Unless Current Phase Explicitly Asks

- Kafka or message queue integration
- Real payment gateway
- Frontend (web, mobile, or SPA)
- Microservices architecture
- Kubernetes deployment
- OAuth or social login
- Email provider integration (SendGrid, SES, etc.)
- SMS provider integration
- Advanced reporting beyond basic revenue/earnings
- Trip photos or file uploads (P9 only)
- Reviews or disputes (P9 only)
- CI/CD beyond basic GitHub Actions (P9 only)
- Observability beyond basic actuator (P9 only)
- Kubernetes or advanced container orchestration

## Phase Gate

If the SRS says a feature is P1, do not implement it in P0.
If the SRS says a feature is P2, do not implement it before P1.

## The Portfolio Proof

The most important thing to build is the concurrent booking test:

```
10 customers try to book the same listing for the same date range.
Only one booking succeeds.
The other 9 requests return 409 LISTING_NOT_AVAILABLE.
The test runs automatically with Testcontainers and PostgreSQL.
```

This proves: database transaction skill, pessimistic locking, idempotency behavior, business rule correctness, API error handling, production-style backend thinking.

Do not get distracted by P2 features before this works.

## Allowed in P0

- Redis for rate limiting and refresh token blacklist
- Docker Compose for local development
- Testcontainers for integration tests
- Flyway for migrations
- SpringDoc OpenAPI for documentation

## Feature Flags

Use feature flags for P0/P1 boundary features:

- `rentflow.booking.require-driver-verification=false` — disables driver verification gate in P0
- These can be removed in later phases when features are fully implemented
